Great! The `notAll` test is passing. The issue with `notParas` might be related to the `:has()` selector implementation. Let me look at the `filterForSelf` method to understand how the intersection works:

Looking back at the main select code:
```java
} else { // E.class, E#id, E[attr] etc. AND
    Elements candidates = findElements(); // take next el, #. etc off queue
    intersectElements(filterForSelf(elements, candidates));
}
```

And the `filterForSelf` method:
```java
// union of both sets, for e.class type selectors
private static Elements filterForSelf(Collection<Element> parents, Collection<Element> candidates) {
    Elements children = new Elements();
    CHILD: for (Element c : candidates) {
        for (Element p : parents) {
            if (c.equals(p)) {
                children.add(c);
                continue CHILD;
            }
        }
    }
    return children;
}
```

So `filterForSelf(elements, candidates)` returns elements that are in both the `elements` set (current results like all p elements) AND the `candidates` set (results from `findElements()` like all elements not matching subquery).

For `p:not(:has(span))`:
- `elements` = {all p elements: p#1, p#2, p#3}  
- `candidates` = {all elements not matching `:has(span)`}
- Result = elements in BOTH sets

So if `:has(span)` matches the third p element, then elements not matching `:has(span)` would be all elements EXCEPT the third p element. So the intersection would be: {p#1, p#2, p#3} ∩ {all elements except p#3 that has span} = {p#1, p#2}.

This should work if `:has(span)` properly identifies elements with span descendants. Let me reconsider the `:has()` implementation:

```java
private Elements has() {
    tq.consume(":has");
    String subQuery = tq.chompBalanced('(',')');
    Validate.notEmpty(subQuery, ":has(el) subselect must not be empty");

    return filterForParentsOfDescendants(elements, select(subQuery, elements));
}
```

Actually, wait! This is different from what I thought. In the `has()` method, it calls `select(subQuery, elements)` where `elements` is the current `this.elements`. This means it only searches among the already-selected elements for the subquery matches.

For `p:not(:has(span))`, when `:has(span)` is processed:
- `this.elements` = the p elements
- `select(span, this.elements)` = span elements that are descendants of the p elements
- Result = p elements that have those span descendants

This should correctly return the third p element that contains span.

So the `:has()` method should work correctly. This means there's an issue with my `:not()` implementation. The problem might be that the logical flow isn't quite right.

